'''
5. You have the following three variables from the arp table of a router:

mac1 = "Internet  10.220.88.29           94   5254.abbe.5b7b  ARPA   FastEthernet4"
mac2 = "Internet  10.220.88.30            3   5254.ab71.e119  ARPA   FastEthernet4"
mac3 = "Internet  10.220.88.32          231   5254.abc7.26aa  ARPA   FastEthernet4"

Process these ARP entries and print out a table of "IP ADDR" to "MAC ADDRESS" mappings. The output should look like following:

             IP ADDR          MAC ADDRESS
-------------------- --------------------
        10.220.88.29       5254.abbe.5b7b
        10.220.88.30       5254.ab71.e119
        10.220.88.32       5254.abc7.26aa


Two columns, 20 characters wide, data right aligned, a header column.
'''

mac1 = "Internet  10.220.88.29           94   5254.abbe.5b7b  ARPA   FastEthernet4"

mac2 = "Internet  10.220.88.30            3   5254.ab71.e119  ARPA   FastEthernet4"

mac3 = "Internet  10.220.88.32          231   5254.abc7.26aa  ARPA   FastEthernet4"

details1 = mac1.split()
details2 = mac2.split()
details3 = mac3.split()

ip_addr1 = details1[1]
ip_addr2 = details2[1]
ip_addr3 = details3[1]

mac_addr1 = details1[3]
mac_addr2 = details2[3]
mac_addr3 = details3[3]

print("{: <20} {: <20}".format("IP_Address", "MAC_Address"))
print('=' * 80)
print("{: <20} {: <20}".format(ip_addr1, mac_addr1))
print("{: <20} {: <20}".format(ip_addr2, mac_addr2))
print("{: <20} {: <20}".format(ip_addr3, mac_addr3))
